result.execSummary:
The defendant Lee Ronnell Jackson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Lee Ronnell Jackson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Lee Ronnell Jackson was found guilty of Theft-Movable Property fr. Person, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Lee Ronnell Jackson was found guilty of Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Additonal statements of support on behalf of the defendant received after the plea and sentencing hearing.

As to Counts 4 & 5:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum and elements received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
As to Counts 1, 2 & 3:  On prosecutor's motion Court dismissed the charges.
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. 

The Court sentenced the defendant
As to Count 4:  to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  6 YEARS with 92 days credit CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence and CONSECUTIVE to Count 5; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 3 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 YEARS.
Court finds defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program or the WI Substance Abuse program.  
Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on 4 YEARS probation.
Conditions of probation are:
- Provide a DNA sample. and pay the DNA surcharge
- Pay extradition costs.  State is unable to access extradition costs and request extradition costs be set at zero.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.
- No contact with the victims
- Pay restitution in the amount of $2079.70 to Willie R.
Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
-  No Cash Bail Posted in this matter
If revoked, Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.
As to Count 5:  to 1 year in the HOC, straight time.
Court waived all other cost, fees, assessments and surcharges due all other costs already assessed by the court.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm. 
Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.
Court advised defendant that he/she may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.  
Court has no objection if this case is transferred to Mississippi to allow the defendant to serve his sentence there.
